New Saudi lobbyist

With help from Taylor Gee, Kaitlyn Burton and Mary Lee

JASTA MINUTE: The Saudis have dispatched Dominique L. Russo, an adviser to the kingdom's General investment Authority, as the country's army of lobbyists prepare a lame-duck push to roll back the law letting 9/11 victims' families sue.

The Saudis hired lobbying sluggers including Squire Patton Boggs and Brownstein Hyatt Farber Schreck and have put pressure on major U.S. companies with assets in the kingdom such as Dow Chemical and General Electric to weigh in against the law, known as the Justice Against Sponsors of Terrorism Act.

TRANSITION: Members of Hillary Clinton's transition team have to recuse themselves from any issues they've lobbied on in the past year and agree not to influence any federal agency they worked on during the transition for one year, POLITICO’s Anna Palmer and Andrew Restuccia report.

MILLIONAIRES CLUB: Democratic Senate candidates in Indiana, North Carolina, Missouri, New Hampshire, Pennsylvania, Nevada and Florida are richer than their Republican opponents, in a year when wealth has become an issue in several key races, POLITICO’s Seung Min Kim writes.

'BUNNY FOR A BOBCAT': Hercules Capital, Apollo Global Management, THL Credit and Ares Management are lobbying against an SEC rule that would stiffen regulations on non-bank lending to small- and middle-market businesses, Bloomberg’s Sridhar Natarajan reports.

FCC WON'T LET ME BE: The brewing lobbying battle over AT&T’s $85 million bid for Time Warner will be a final battle for FCC Chairman Tom Wheeler, a former cable and wireless lobbyist who became a tough regulator, Cecilia Kang writes for The New York Times.

Industry figures who cheered Wheeler's appointment but later expressed frustration with his posture include Michael Powell, president of the National Cable and Telecommunications Association, and James Cicconi, who recently retired as AT&T's top lobbyist.
